    "summarization": {
        "a": "This figure set presents the evolution of volatile byproducts during surface treatment, monitored using mass spectrometry. Panels (a) through (c) show mass spectra recorded under different temperatures and pulse conditions. In panel (a), increased temperatures from 100\u202f\u00b0C to 300\u202f\u00b0C result in stronger signals for characteristic m/z peaks such as CO (m/z 28), CO\u2082 (m/z 44), HF (m/z 20), and fluorinated fragments like CF\u2083 (m/z 69), indicating more extensive ligand decomposition or desorption. Panel (b) confirms that radical pulses alone do not contribute significant gaseous species, while panel (c) compares product profiles with and without O\u2082 or radical exposure on HfO\u2082 surfaces, revealing enhanced release of volatile fragments when radicals are used. Panel (d) traces the temporal evolution of specific product signals during the radical pulse, where species like CO and CO\u2082 exhibit sharp rises followed by gradual decline. Collectively, the data support the conclusion that elevated temperatures and radical co-reactants increase etch byproducts, validating the role of thermal and chemical activation in ALE."
    },
